HE J fJ J S\nULTRAVIOLET CJ\nLIGHT IN SUN- Y, M WfflU f J\nSHINE. WITHOUT C\nTHIS OZONE LAYER,\nPLANTS AND y l*y\nANIMALS WOULD J/ J\nBE BURNT TO Cjr\nA CRISP. r J\nJfJ Oe see ~-Adf\nJ r J BY REFLECTED A\nr J f LIGHT. SUNSHINE 4'Vj\nJ J (OR ARTIFICIAL LIGHT)\nJ FALLS UPON OBJECTS AND\nJ IS REFLECTED TO OUR EYES,\nS AVS s^BETTERJdS^N^\n\u00a9IKE RADIO RECEIVERS,\nHUMAN EVES ARE TUNED J MUSK A 41\nTO THE WAVELENGTHS 11 VjfffrllW'fiiPP\u2019 1\nOF THE ATOMIC LIGHT mii gST/fl\nENERGY BROADCAST Wjn. ST* 7E|\nBY THE SUN. IF ONE'S\nEYES ARE 'OFF THE\nBEAM\" HE NEEDS MG\nSPECTACLES FOR CLEAR VISION, 1 MV' I \\W/\nReport on Reconversion\nBy Henri Tussenbroek\nA recent survey has been re\nleased by the C. E. D. (Commit\ntee for Economic Development)\nwith headquarters at 285 Madi\nson Ave., in New York. An\nanalysis has been made of con\nditions across the nation to de\ntermine just how long a period\nof return to noramlly may be\nexpected. The committee has\ngone into great detail and\nweighed matters from several\nangles of possibility.\nThe C. E. D. has recommended\nthe establishment of a Presi\ndent\u2019s commission on full em\nployment and of a joint congres\nsional committee on full employ\nment as a means df developing,\ncoordinating and integrating a\nprogram of measures to deal\nwith the many problems involved\nin achieving a prosperous and\nstable economy.\nAccording to the C. E. D. re\nconversion may proceed very\nrapidly in view of a spot check\nof 84 of the major cities and war\nproduction centers. Of these 84\ncities reporting, 25 show recon\nversion well under way with no\nmajor unemployment problems\nindicated. Three cities will re\nquire a three-month period; 20\ncities six months and 12 a year\nfor full reconversion. It should\nbe noted here that according to\nthe reports received three cities\ndo not expect grave unemploy\nment problems.\nThirteen cities did not list the\ntime required for full reconver\nsion, not having sufficient data\nat this time to do so. One com\nmunity reported peak of unem\nployment in 1947. Ten cities do\nnot now foresee the day when\nall the unemployment can be re\nlieved.\nWalter D. Fuller, chairman of\nthe Field Development Division,\nwho released the C. E. D. report\nto the nation, said: \u201cI wish to\nemphasize that this is a spot\npicture of reconversion. This in\nno sense of the word a national\nsummation or forecast of the\nemployment situation. What we\nare giving is a report of the pace\nat which reconversion is being\naccomplished, or can be accom\nplished, in the opinion of local\nbusiness leaders. Their estimates\nrepresent the considered judg\nment of these men and are based\non three years of work as chair\nmen of their local C. E. Ds.\n\u201cDuring the war years many\ngovernmental agencies, and\nmany non-governmental groups;\nof which C. E. D. is one, worked\nurging private business towards\npeacetime expansion and conse\nquent high levels of productive\nemployment. Today we are, per\nhaps, measuring some results of\nthis three year effort. The im\nmediate business reactions to V-J\nDay seem to indicate that busi\nness is ready to go ahead if\nsound policies by industry, labor,\nagriculture and government are\nsuch as to encourage the planned\nexpansion.\n\u201cMany factors can influence\nthe future stages of reconver\nsion. As one example, many\nworkers seem to have dropped\nout of labor force. In a few\nmonths they may come back for\njobs. It is unknown how many\npeople today are going to draw\ntheir unemployment compensa\ntion and retire from paid em\nployment; how many are on va\ncations; how many who find it\nunnecessory to work may do so\nif they find the kind of jobs\nthey want. Therefore there is no\ntrue measure of the actual, in\nvoluntary and temporary' unem\nployment at this time.\u201d\nChairman Fuller also ex\nplained how the problem was ap\nproached. According to his state\nment, when a community was or\nganized the first step of the local\nprogram was a survey in which\nemployers were asked three im\nportant questions, among others:\n(1) How many workers they em\nployed in 1940; (2) How many\nthey employed at the time of the\nsurvey; (3) How many they ex\npect to employ in the postwar\nperiod.\nBefore an employer could ans\nwer that third question he had to\ncomplete his postwar prepara\ntions for expansion, which was\none of the principal objections of\nC. E. D.\nAs estimates of these indivi\ndual employers were completed\nthey were assembled by com\nmunities and given to the Fed\neral Reserve Bank in Washing\nton, D. C. as reference for gov\nernment agencies and other in\nterested parties.\nIn order to get an adequate\npicture of the national effort\ntowards reconversion and the\npresent estimates as to the time\nneeded for a return to prewar\nconditions we refer here to the\nfigures from the report of C. E. D.\nThe 25 cities which have either\ncompleted reconversion, or have\nno major unemployment prob\nlems are\u2014New Haven, Conn.;\nBoston, and Lawrence, Mass.;\nUtica, N. Y.; Wilmington, Del.;\nTrenton, and Newark, N. J.;\nHarrisburg, and Philadelphia,\nPa.; Canton, Ohio; Charlotte,\nN. C.; Richmond, Va.; Tampa,\nFla.; Grand Rapids and Saginau,\nMich.; Des Moines, la.; Rockford,\n111., Indianapolis, Ind.; San An\ntonio, Fort Worth, El Paso, and\nAustin, Texas; Sacramento, Oak\nland and Long Beach, Cali.\nThree cities where a three\nmonth reconversion period is re\nquire are Akron and Cincinnati,\nOhio; and Bridgeport, Conn.\nThe twenty cities which re\nquire a six month period are Wa\nterbury, Conn.; Albany, N. Y.;\nBuffalo, N. Y. (six to eight\nmonths, its report said); Eliza\nbeth, and Jersey City, N. J.;\nYoungstown, Toledo, Dayton,\nOhio; Washington, D. C.; Birm\ningham, Ala.; Flint, Pontiac and\nDetroit, Mich.; Sioux City, la.;\nMilwaukee, Wis.; Memphis,\nTenn.; Kansas City, Mo.; Shreve\nport, La.; Houston, Texas; San-\nFrancisco, Cal.\nThose cities requiring a full\nyear for full reconversion include\n\u2014Providence, R. I.; Syracuse,\nN. Y.; Erie, Pa.; Columbus, Ohio;\nAtlanta, Ga. (although sixty per\ncent of the unemployed will be\nrelieved within six months, if\nthey want the jobs); Dulieth,\nMinn.; Seattle, and Spokane,\nWash.; San Diego, Cali.; South\nBend, Ind. (13,000 of the esti\nmated unemployment will be re\nlieved in six to eight months and\nthe balance shortly thereafter);\nMiami, Fla.\nTwelve cities which did not es\ntimate the time required for full\nreconversion are\u2014Rochester, and\nNew York City, N. Y.; Allen\ntown, Pa.; Cleveland, Ohio; Balti\nmore, Md.; Nashville, Tenn. (has\n100,815 employed and 3,500 un\nemployed since V-J Day. Believe\nsupply and demand in area of\ndifferent types of unemployed\ncan be absorbed by jobs avail\nable when industry able to secure\nsufficient suitable help to get on\nforty hour basis); Little Rock,\nArk. (Report says unable to es\ntimate how soon unemployment\nwill be absorbed. Some jobs avail\nable now; wages unacceptable to\nunemployed. Additional 2,000 re\nturning veterans will come into\nlabor market next six months.\nArkansas was in No. 4 labor mar\nket area. Many workers sent to\ncritical shortage areas and un\nable to estimate how many have\nreturned or if others will return\nin near future. Vigorous effort\nbeing made to increase job op\nportunities through direct ex\npansion of present industries\nand opening new ones); St. Louis,\nMo.; Wichita, Kansas; Tacoma,\nWash.; Glendale, Cal.\nNorfolk, Va., needs a three\nmonths period to determine the\nsituation. (Its report says: \u201cThere\nhas been an announcement of an\nticipated layoffs in the Norfolk\nNavy Yard, but it is expected that\nthese will be gradual and that the\nforce will be stabilized at some\nthing like a normal level shortly\nafter the first of the year. If this\nworks out and if contemplated\nlayoffs at the Naval operating\nbase and the private shipyards\nmaterialize, two things will hap\npen\u2014a great many of these work\ners will be absorbed in our private\nindustries, in service operations,\nbuilding construction where there\nis an acute shortage at the mo\nment and many of these workers\nwill return to their homes in near\nby and distant parts of the coun\ntry. W therefore feel \u2014that while\nwe undoubtedly face this area a\nmajor readjustment problem, it is\nunlikely, unless Government op\nerations are curtailed more rapid\nly than we anticipate, that we will\nhave a serious unemployment sit\nuation to face.)\nTen communities which cannot\nnow foresee the day when all the\nunemployment may be relieved\nare:\u2014Springfield, and Worcester,\nMass.; Wilkes Barre, Pa.; Chatta\nnooga, Tenn. (estimates 75 per\ncent to be relieved in six months),\nEvansville, Ind.; Louisville, Ky.;\nMinneapolis, Minn.; Denver,\nColo.; (although no grave unem\nployment problem is anticipat\ned); Portland, Ore.; Berkeley,\nCal.\nFall River does not expect an\nunemployment problem until\nJanuary of 1947, which it can\nmeet, its report says, if only new\nindustries come to Fall River.\nSuch is the report as assembled\nfrom the statements of these\nvarious cities on our continent.\nIn an effort to bring understand\ning of the problems involved the\nC. E. D. also gives a clear view\nof the economic difficulties to be\nmet and how to attack them.\nIt thereby states that the pri\nvate sector of our economy will\nhave to provide the great bulk of\nthe 7 to 10 million new peace\ntime jobs needed, inasmuch as it\nhas provided 90% of total em\nployment in the past and there is\nlittle likelihood of any important\nchange in that ratio in the future.\nWith agriculture, a declining\nsource of jobs, and industrial em\nployment diminishing now that\nthe war is over, most of the need\ned job expansion must come in\nthe field of trade and service occu\npations. The 30% t 045% increase\nin these output of goods and serv\nices as compared with 1940 neces\nsary to provide these additional\njobs \u201cwill call for a free flow of\nideas and willingness on the part\nof hundreds of thousands of en\nterprisers and millions of inves\ntors to risk billions of dollars\u201d the\ncommittee declares.\nThe committee views this ex\npansion as an objective in which\nbusiness, labor and government\nshare joint interest and respon\nsibility. While this joint interest\ncenters in a high and rising stan\ndard of living the committee con\nsiders its roots to be in a steadily\nexpanding productivity with the\nfruits of such productivity passed\nalong as lower prices and higher\nLAURA JONES\nCERTIFIED ELECTROLOGIST\n\"Permanent Removal of Unwanted Hair\u201d\nFree Consultation\n75 Pratt St., Suite 300 Tel. 6-8365\nHartford, Conn.\nProtect your home now with GILCON PAINTS\nSOLD DIRECT FROM OUR FACTORY\nA-l OUTSIDE WHITE $2.95 per gal.\nunsurpassed for durability, whiteness, covering, ease of\napplication and economy. Designed for this New England\nclimate.\nALSO \u2014Porch Paints, Trim Paints, Concrete Enamels and\nInterior Finishes of outstanding quality.\nWE DELIVER\nGilcon Paint Chemical Co.\n133 Grove Street, Hartford, Conn.\nPHONE 6 9596\nWilliam P. Quish\nFuneral Service\nDAY and NIGHT AMBULANCE SERVICE\nCOMPLETE MODERN FACILITIES\nTEL. MANCHESTER 4340\n225 Main Street Manchester\n|Javei\\\nSiirgieaf (Jo\nManufacturers and Expert Fitters of\nTRUSSES ARTIFICIAL LIMBS\nELASTIC STOCKINGS ORTHOPAEDIC BRACES\nHospital. Beds, Wheel Chairs, Crutches, Commodes\nFOR RENT OR SALE\nARCH SUPPORTERS MADE AFTER PLASTER CASTS\nBACK SUPPORTERS, ABDOMINAL SUPPORTS\n279 Asylum St. (near Ann St.) Hartford 6-6361\nmake pm;\nto give your clothes EMPIRE SANITONE\ncleaning.\nEMPIRE expert dry cleaning leaves clothes looking\nlike new.\n286 Sheldon Street, Hartford\nwages for a constantly expaad\ning output of goods and services\n\u201cBoth employers and labor\nleaders,\u201d says the report, profit\nin the long run in pursuit of tfiis\ncommon goal by opposing restric\ntive policies that lower output\nand raise costs.\u201d\nBusiness employers owe it to\ntheir workers as well as to their\nstockholders to operate their en\nterprises at a profit, the report\ndeclares, since \"without profits\nthe businessmen, as job-makers,\ncannot provide expanding job ep\n(Continued on Page 7)\nFIVE","height":"27112","width":"19723"}}
